The '''Neo-Tiwanakan''' or Pseudo-Tiwanakan [[architecture]] is a style developed by the architect [[Emilio Villanueva|Emilio Villanueva Peñaranda]] between the years 1930 and 1948 inspired in the designs of the [[Pre-Columbian]] archeological site of [[Tiwanaku]] in [[Bolivia]].<ref name="SocArq">{{cite book |author=Browman, David   |title=La Sociedad arqueológica de Bolivia y su influencia en el desarrollo de la práctica arqueológica en Bolivia |trans-title=The archeological society of Bolivia and its influence in the development of the archeological practice in Bolivia |url=http://www.arqueobolivia.com/revistas/23_51_32-1222738970.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=1 February 2010 |series=Nuevos Aportes |volume=4 |year=2007 |location=La Paz, Bolivia |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name="GuiaLP">{{cite book |author1=Pérez, Martín   |author2=Boero Rojo, Hugo |author3=de la Riva, Miroslava |editor=Unión  de Ciudades Capitales Iberoamericanas |title=Guía de La Paz |trans-title=La Paz guide |url=https://books.google.com/?id=D3e7AAAAIAAJ |series=Guías UCCI |volume=13 |year=1990 |publisher= |location=Madrid, Spain |language=Spanish |isbn=978-84-87771-02-6 |oclc=433846494 }}</ref>

==Origins==
The architect Emilio Villanueva popularized the Neo-Tiwanakan architecture in the city of [[La Paz]] during the decade of the 1930s. The inspiration for these designs was the blueprints for ideal reconstructions of Tiwanaku elaborated by Edmund Kiss in 1937; these designs were adapted by Villanueva to give them an urban and contemporaneous style.<ref name="SocArq" />

